					<b class="font-semibold">Hi, I’m Chris Spurlock.</b>
				</p>

				<p>
					I’m a developer with a journalist’s brain, a designer’s eye, and a builder’s heart. Over the last decade, I’ve moved fluidly between
					storytelling, strategy, and software—whether that meant pioneering interactive infographics in a legacy newsroom, launching enterprise-grade
					WordPress builds, or obsessing over accessibility and user empathy. The through-line? Relentless curiosity and self-directed mastery.
				</p>

				<p>
					I spent my early career in journalism, where a lecture on interactive storytelling lit a fire that never really burned out. There was no
					formal training track, so I built one: learning D3, jQuery, and CSS on nights and weekends to bring stories to life in the browser. Since
					then, I’ve applied that same energy to every challenge I’ve encountered—whether it was leading a digital transformation at a major
					newspaper, coding custom themes from scratch, or jumping into a JS framework I’d never used before... because the project needed it
					<em>yesterday</em>.
				</p>

				<p>
					These days, I’m the COO and UI lead at
					<a href="https://thekestrel.co" class="text-fuchsia-700 hover:text-fuchsia-900" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The Kestrel Co.</a
					>, a boutique dev agency where I help shape both the work and the workflows. I’m known for wearing many hats—sometimes in the same meeting.
					Design audits, accessibility reviews, CSS bug hunts, pricing strategy, proposals, GTM tracking setups—I’ve done them all. And I believe my
					superpower is making teams feel calm, collaborative, and inspired.
				</p>

				<p>
					AI is changing the game—and I’m here for it. I see AI as a teammate, not a threat: a pair programmer, a rubber duck, and a research
					assistant rolled into one. I’m already using GPT to debug, to explore new frameworks, to prototype ideas, and to challenge my own thinking.
					I’m excited by what this means for the craft of development—and for those of us who care deeply about the people on the other side of the
					screen.
				</p>

